  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by disguising its true source. This is done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a serious federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Fines**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years per offense, depending on the severity and circumstances of the crime.\n- **Asset Forfeiture**: Authorities may seize funds and assets involved in or gained from money laundering activities.\n\nMoney laundering laws are also enforced at the state level, and penalties can vary depending on the jurisdiction and the specifics of the case. Additionally, **international organizations** and treaties, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, work to combat money laundering globally.\n\nEngaging in money laundering can also lead to additional charges related to the underlying criminal activity that generated the illicit funds, compounding the legal consequences.",
